Author-Name: PAUL OYER 
Title: The Making of an Investment Banker: Stock Market Shocks, Career Choice, and Lifetime Income 
Abstract:
 I show that stock market shocks have important and lasting effects on the
 careers of MBAs. Stock market conditions while MBA students are in school
 have a large effect on whether they go directly to Wall Street upon
 graduation. Further, starting on Wall Street immediately upon graduation
 causes a person to be more likely to work there later and to earn, on
 average, substantially more money. The empirical results suggest that
 investment bankers are largely "made" by circumstance rather than "born"
 to work on Wall Street. Copyright (c) 2008 The American Finance Association. 
